Title: MCMC CONVERGENCE DIAGNOSTICS: A "REVIEwww"  
Author: Kerrie L. Mengersen, QUT, Christian P. Robert, CREST-INSEE, Paris, France Darren Robb, Andrew George and Sonia Knight 
Keyword: Key Words: Markov chain Monte Carlo, asymptotics, stationary distribution, ergodicity, renewal theory, CLT, parallel chains, mixing, subsampling, CODA, genetics, hidden Markov chains, stochastic volatility. Resume Mots cle Monte Carlo par cha^nes de Markov, convergence, renouvellement, ergodicite, theoreme central limit, melangeance, CODA, sous-echantillonnage, cha^nes de Markov cachees, volatilite stochastique.  
Note: Assistance from  is gratefully acknowledged.  
Date: April 27, 1998  
Address: Australia  1323, Universite Paris 5, Paris, France  
Affiliation: Brisbane,  Chantal Guihenneuc-Jouyaux, URA CNRS  
Abstract: This review paper aims at presenting the various convergence diagnostics available in the literature in a cohesive and conceptually consecutive manner. To this effect, we attempt classification according to several filters, as well as a description of a twin Web site, which aims at keeping track of the on-going research on the topic. We also illustrate the performance of the different diagnostics in several advanced applications, including mixtures and hidden Markov models, stochastic volatility models, genetic models, and HIV progression models, based on earlier and present experiments. Cet article passe en revue les diverses techniques existantes pour controler la convergence des algorithmes de Monte Carlo par cha^nes de Markov, en proposant diverses typologies de classement. Il est couple a un site Web dedie au recensement de ces techniques et a leur actualisation. Nous montrons egalement le comportement des methodes de controle dans le cadre d'exemples detailles comme les melanges, les cha^nes de Markov cachees, la modelisation de la progression du virus HIV, la detection de marqueurs (QTL) dans l'ADN et un modele de volatilite stochastique. y Members of the McCube workshop, held monthly at CREST between 1995 and 1998, are heartfully thanked for providing some of the material contained in this paper as well as for helpful discussions and criticisms. 
